  "prompt": "What is the meaning of Ishraq in Islam?",
  "response": "In Islam, the term \"Ishraq\" refers to the time of day shortly after sunrise when the sun has risen and is visible in the sky. It is associated with a specific prayer known as the \"Salat al-Ishraq,\" which is a voluntary (nafl) prayer that Muslims can perform after the sun has fully risen. This prayer is typically performed around 15-20 minutes after sunrise and is considered a time of great blessing and spirituality.\n\nThe practice of praying at this time is encouraged in various hadiths (sayings of the Prophet Muhammad), emphasizing the benefits and virtues of performing this prayer. It is seen as an opportunity for spiritual reflection and connection with God, marking the start of a new day with worship and gratitude.\n\nIn a broader sense, \"Ishraq\" can also symbolize enlightenment or illumination, signifying the light of guidance and knowledge in one's spiritual journey.",
